Software Used
Cisco Packet Tracer
Theory

DNS (Domain Name System) is used to translate human-readable domain names (like www.google.com) into IP addresses (like 8.8.8.8).

Computers communicate using IP addresses, not names.
DNS acts like a phonebook of the internet.
It makes it easier for users to access websites without remembering numeric IPs.
Working of DNS (short)
User enters a domain name.
DNS server checks its database.
If found, it returns the corresponding IP address.
The client uses that IP to communicate.
Procedure
Step 1: Open Packet Tracer
Launch Cisco Packet Tracer.
Step 2: Create Network Topology
Add the following devices:
1 Server (DNS Server)
2 PCs
1 Switch
Connect all devices using copper straight-through cables.
Step 3: Configure IP Addresses
For Server:
Go to Desktop → IP Configuration
Assign:
IP Address: 192.168.1.2
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0
For PC1:
IP Address: 192.168.1.3
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0
DNS Server: 192.168.1.2
For PC2:
IP Address: 192.168.1.4
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0
DNS Server: 192.168.1.2
Step 4: Configure DNS on Server
Click on Server
Go to Services → DNS
Turn DNS service ON
Add record:
Name: www.example.com
Address: 192.168.1.2
Click Add
Step 5: Test Configuration
Go to PC → Desktop → Command Prompt

Type:

ping www.example.com

OR use browser:

Open Web Browser
Enter: www.example.com

Result:

The DNS server was successfully configured.
The domain name www.example.com was resolved to its IP address, and communication was verified using ping/browser.
